WHO   — Transparency & Explainability — the principle that decisions affecting people should be inspectable and explainable — the demand for a 'right to explanation,' against the opacity of large models and the limits of post-hoc explanation
WHAT  — the principle that decisions affecting people should be inspectable and explainable — the demand for a 'right to explanation,' against the opacity of large models and the limits of post-hoc explanation
WHERE — GOV · AI Ethics & Governance — David's charter + the global landscape (2016–2026)  Framework inputs: the Bill of Rights; the Governance Ontology; the principles; the cases; the instruments  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)
WHY   — It is the precondition for all the others: you cannot contest, audit, or hold accountable a decision you cannot see — yet the most capable systems are the least legible, which is the standing tension.
HOW   — Crystallized from David's normative artifacts + the cited ethics-and-governance record.

